  &lt;td class=&quot;diff-addedline&quot;&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;diffchange diffchange-inline&quot;&gt;The onset of [[World War I]] gave the federal government the opportunity to take action against Haywood and the IWW. Using the newly passed [[Espionage Act of 1917]] as justification, the [[Department of Justice]] raided forty-eight IWW meeting halls in September 1917.&amp;lt;ref name=siitonen&amp;gt;Siitonen.&amp;lt;/ref&amp;gt; The Department of Justice then proceeded to arrest 165 IWW members for &quot;conspiring to hinder the draft, encourage desertion, and intimidate others in connection with labor disputes.&quot;&amp;lt;ref name=zinn-372-373&amp;gt;Zinn, 372-373.&amp;lt;/ref&amp;gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
  &lt;td class=&quot;diff-marker&quot;&gt;â&lt;/td&gt;
  &lt;td class=&quot;diff-deletedline&quot;&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;diffchange diffchange-inline&quot;&gt;In [[1918]], Haywood was convicted of violating federal [[Espionage Act of 1917|espionage]] and [[Sedition Act of 1918|sedition]] acts by calling a strike during wartime.  Sentenced to prison by Judge [[Kenesaw Mountain Landis]], Haywood skipped his [[bail|bond]] while out on appeal and fled to the [[Soviet Union]] where he became an advisor to the [[Bolshevik]] government.  Haywood died in [[Moscow]] in 1928. Half of his ashes were buried in [[the Kremlin]] and an urn containing the other half of his ashes was sent to Chicago and buried near a monument to the [[Haymarket Riot|Haymarket anarchists]].&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
  &lt;td class=&quot;diff-marker&quot;&gt;+&lt;/td&gt;
  &lt;td class=&quot;diff-addedline&quot;&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
  &lt;td colspan=&quot;2&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/td&gt;
  &lt;td class=&quot;diff-marker&quot;&gt;+&lt;/td&gt;
  &lt;td class=&quot;diff-addedline&quot;&gt;&lt;div&gt;In April 1918, Haywood and 100 of the arrested IWW members began their trial, presided over by Judge [[Kenesaw Mountain Landis]]. The trial lasted last five months, the longest criminal trial up to that time; Haywood himself testified for three days.&amp;lt;ref name=zinn-372-373 /&amp;gt; All 101 defendents were found guilty, and Haywood (along with fourteen others) was sentenced to twenty years in prison.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
  &lt;td colspan=&quot;2&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/td&gt;
  &lt;td class=&quot;diff-marker&quot;&gt;+&lt;/td&gt;
  &lt;td class=&quot;diff-addedline&quot;&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
  &lt;td colspan=&quot;2&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/td&gt;
  &lt;td class=&quot;diff-marker&quot;&gt;+&lt;/td&gt;
  &lt;td class=&quot;diff-addedline&quot;&gt;&lt;div&gt;Despite the efforts of his supporters, Haywood was unable to overturn the conviction. In 1921, Haywood skipped his [[bail|bond]] while out on appeal and fled to the [[Russia]].&amp;lt;ref name=siitonen /&amp;gt; He became an advisor to the [[Bolshevik]] government,{{fact}} and spent the rest of his life there.  Haywood died in [[Moscow]] in 1928. Half of his ashes were buried in [[the Kremlin]] and an urn containing the other half of his ashes was sent to Chicago and buried near a monument to the [[Haymarket Riot|Haymarket anarchists]].{{fact}}&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
